Hi Noopur, I have been working on adding the @Suite support that got Alex asking me to update to JUnit 5.8.1 in the first place.  I found that there is another module: junit-platform-suite-engine that supports this at runtime.  I have recently added this to Orbit.  This engine is found dynamically and it interprets the @Suite annotations and then calls another test engine to do the actual testing (e.g. it finds the @SelectClasses annotation and sends these to the other engine on the classpath).

I have it working for "Run as Junit Test", but I can't get it working for "Run as Junit Test Plugin".  In the 2nd case it finds the junit-platform-suite-engine but cannot find another test engine.  I have tried adding junit-jupiter-engine to the plug-in's .classpath, it's dependencies, and as a JVM parameter for the launch configuration, but still I get a message that the junit-platform-suite-engine did not find another test engine.

Patch Set 1:

Plot twist: It’s not that my seemingly unrelated code change changed the iteration order of the HashMap. It’s that the tests use a reordering-tolerant file comparator (org.eclipse.cdt.managedbuilder.testplugin.ManagedBuildTestHelper.compareMakefiles()) that let the test succeed as long as reorderings were the only differences. Only when my change caused a removed line, the comparison failed and output a diff *including* the reordering that was not caused by my change but had been there all along.

It’s probably still worth going ahead with the LinkedHashMap. It preserves the insertion order, which as far as I examined seems to come from the toolchain definitions (not from other nondeterministic sources), which is probably good enough. I’m still figuring out the best way of finding which benchmark files should be adjusted to the new (hopefully stable) ordering so that future test failures will not generate spurious reordering diffs.

3) It uses String keys instead of File keys.  I assume hash/equals is faster for String keys vs File keys.  Mainly based on what the javadoc for File.hashCode says:

     * Computes a hash code for this abstract pathname.  Because equality of

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Thanks Thomas for working on it. I would prefer a rock solid solution even if its slower. The time we lose by broken heuristics is probably higher then the additional time to read all files.

I don't think that's a good idea in current JGit. Check-in/Check-out and merges might become very slow; and some intermediary buffers might get too large. EGit will get a preference to set this buffer size in the range of 8kB (as it is now) up to 128kB.

That is good enough. If JGit mis-identifies a file, users always have the option of specifying via .gitattributes whether a file is binary or text. And if it misses a CRLF after the first 128kB, at least you'll become aware of the problem and can fix it. (Or, again, mark the file as binary via .gitattributes.) Mixed line endings are a nuisance.

Not using a buffer at all would mean that content may, in the worst case, need to be scanned twice. JGit internally chains streams, so that would become difficult, or would again need unbounded buffers, which is a no-go.

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> EGit will get a preference to set this buffer size in the range of 8kB (as it is now) up to 128kB.

Please at least give us the option to configure it to deterministic behavior.
As long as it only doubles the time of operation because of twice scanning i'll be very fine with that. I rather have the time doubled then to live in uncertainty.

As a user i do not want to think about marking files binary manually. Mixed newlines happen and we got to live with it. I thought autocrlf should fix them.
